# Domain edge cases — [APP_NAME]

The gotchas of this project's domain. Not business rules (those are in
`business-rules.md`) — these are the **weird scenarios** that look like
ordinary cases but break ordinary code. Each entry names the case, why
it's tricky, how this project handles it, and the anti-pattern that's
been tried.

This file is read by `rsct_get_knowledge(category="domain-edge-cases")`
and by `rsct_persona_review` (QA persona). Spec phase surfaces relevant
edge cases when proposing functionality in their area — so the proposal
acknowledges "this needs to handle the PJ-without-state-registration case"
before code is written.

**Bias correction:** Without this file, Claude proposes happy-path
solutions that pass demos but break on real data. With it, the spec
phase enumerates the cases up front and the testing strategy covers them.

---

## When to capture an entry here

Capture an edge case when **any** of the following is true:

- A bug was caused by an assumption that turned out to be wrong (timezone,
nullability, character set, document format, identity uniqueness, etc.).
- A customer report exposed a scenario the team didn't think of.
- Design review surfaces a case that requires explicit handling (don't
just decide — capture it so the next session knows).
- A test was added specifically to cover a non-obvious case. Cross-reference
the test here.
- A regulatory or contractual obligation creates a case (e.g., "international
customers without CPF require alternate identification").

## When NOT to capture here

- Business invariants that hold across all cases → `business-rules.md`.
- Generic programming gotchas (null checks, integer overflow) — those are
baseline craftsmanship.
- One-off data quality issues — those are runbook entries, not domain edge
cases (unless they recur or signal a structural issue, then capture).
- Performance edge cases ("query is slow when N>10k") → those usually
belong in incident log or architecture notes.

