## Entry schema

Each entry follows this exact structure:

```
### DEC-NNN — <short case name>
- **Case:** <the scenario in concrete terms — "customer is a foreign
  legal entity (PJ Estrangeira) without Brazilian CPF/CNPJ">
- **Why it's tricky:** <what makes ordinary code break — "validation
  assumed all customers have CPF; foreign customers have only passport
  + tax-id of origin country">
- **This project handles it by:** <the chosen approach, with file:line
  pointers — "`Customer.taxId` is a sealed-class union of `CPF | CNPJ |
  ForeignTaxId(country, value)`; serialization at
  [`CustomerSerializer.kt:88`](src/.../CustomerSerializer.kt#L88)">
- **Tests covering it:** <file:line of the test that asserts the handling.
  If no test yet, mark `<no test — gap captured 2026-XX-XX>` so the
  testing strategy in §G picks it up>
- **Anti-pattern (do NOT do this):** <the wrong way someone has tried or
  would naturally try — "do NOT add a `country == 'BR'` check to coerce
  foreign taxId into CPF format; that loses the foreign tax-id and
  re-introduces bug fixed in INC-XXX">
- **Related:** <BRs that govern this case, INC entries that revealed it,
  glossary terms, vendor entries (e.g., a KYC vendor that has its own
  handling)>
- **Captured:** <YYYY-MM-DD> by <dev|claude>
```

Numbering: DEC-001+ sequential, append-only.

